My Intentions. 

This portrait of me was taken on my reservation back in 2016 by my good friend @tomag_tohnolig. She forced me to take it but hey I’m grateful now lol. Since I was a teen I’ve always been creative, always having a particular way of seeing life in a different color. As my career progressed I started to work with brands I never even thought would be possible. As time went on, I continued to feel bored and a bit empty with my work because I was scared to document the things I truly cared about. That being my roots. The fear coming from not being raised or educated within the community. My great grandma was sent to one of the American Indian boarding schools from Arizona to South California, hence how my side of the family came to be. 

Western has always been my eye, but once it started to become trendy I had mixed feelings about. To see people diving into the western stuff with sometimes no respect to the lifestyle or history. I feel the need to do my part beyond just shooting fashion models and commercial brands. I am excited to start using my voice for something bigger than me. Now is the moment. To preserve and share the beauty and struggles of my people while also documenting my own process of discovery. Cause over time I’ve met a lot of natives with similar stories to mine, so thank you for sharing your hearts with me and bringing me some comfort in this odd displaced feeling. 

Just thought I’d share. I am grateful for where my journey has brought me, its prepared me for what’s next. Stay tuned for some exciting projects that are already in the works ❤️ 

Not the end of a chapter. A beginning of a new book.

AUTHENTICALLY SHALLOW

During Covid, as western started to become trendy.. I assumed indigenous faces would be next. 

Premonitions of the corporate greed dressing up marketing campaigns pretending to care about indigenous stories. 

I challenge all of these corporate fashion brands to actually share these stories. If you’re going to hunt for the shallow beauty, at least pretend to care about the culture and resilience that creates it. Make a difference, don’t just romanticize previous Americana ideas of it. 

You’re suppose to represent authenticity. Now practice it.

Donate. Help the community. Grow empathy with your audience. We don’t need more romantic fluff pieces.

Last year I teamed up with @ianmunsick & @carolinemunsick to hand the mic over to the voices of the west ⚡️⚡️ idk how or why.. but they somehow trusted me enough to let me direct and shoot a feature length documentary on some of our close friends, the Indigenous Cowboys & Cowgirls of the west. 
We’ll be having a private premier during NFR in Vegas! Stay tuned for the trailer! 
Insanely grateful to have been a part of this and excited for everyone to see it. Voices Of The West will be publicly released in early 2024.

Huge shoutout to @_nickrubino for being the glue and bringing this edit alive. Literally don’t know what would have done without you brother. 

Shoutout @syellowtail and the yellowtails for treating me like family and always reminding me what gratitude is. Dare I say Stephen is the ULTIMATE COWBOY. I know he’ll love that 😂

Shoutout to @sammyjobird1 for being one of the most down to earth people, just jam packed with talent. Always a joy to be around and always shows up when it matters the most. 

Shoutout to the legend @dougiefreshhall This man is just getting started. Excited for more of you peep to meet him in this documentary, he’ll bring you laughter and tears. AHO cousin brother nephew. 

And huge shoutout to @ianmunsick & @carolinemunsick The king and queen of the west. Just wait for it guys. The authenticity behind the moves they’re make is going to stir the pot in all the best of ways.

Being able to see film sims through the viewfinder lights up every photographer brain with inspiration. I created some of my own in camera presets that I’ll share soon. Still one of my personal favs that I’ve done over the years. Circa 2020

On a lot of these cowboy shoots it’s a lot of run and gun shooting. On this one specifically, on the first morning of filming I had visualized the edit and the music. From there I was able to to film with a purpose for every shot. The idea required its own score, so when I got home I had just recorded my guitar through my phone and then did all the sound design and mixing from there as well as the edit. Then @walkerider wrote the script for the voice over which was performed by the well known Boots Sutherland
